<mml:msub><mml:mrow><mml:mi>N</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>c</mml:mi><mml:mi class="MJX-variant" mathvariant="normal">′</mml:mi><mml:mi>g</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:msub><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mrow><mml:mi>I</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mi>c</mml:mi></mml:msub><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mrow><mml:mi>I</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>c</mml:mi><mml:mi class="MJX-variant" mathvariant="normal">′</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:msub><mml:mo>)</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:mrow></mml:mfrac></mml:math><graphic xlink:href="13059_2019_1922_Article_Equb.gif" position="anchor"/></alternatives></disp-formula>where <italic>X</italic><sub><italic>c</italic></sub> = (<italic>X</italic><sub><italic>c</italic>1</sub>, <italic>X</italic><sub><italic>c</italic>2</sub>, …<italic>X</italic><sub><italic>cg</italic></sub>, …<italic>X</italic><sub><italic>cm</italic></sub>) are the mutation allele read counts for cell <italic>c</italic> and <italic>N</italic><sub><italic>c</italic></sub> = (<italic>N</italic><sub><italic>c</italic>1</sub>, <italic>N</italic><sub><italic>c</italic>2</sub>, …<italic>N</italic><sub><italic>cg</italic></sub>, …<italic>N</italic><sub><italic>cm</italic></sub>) are the total read counts at these sites. More intuitively, if cells <italic>c</italic> and <italic>c</italic>′ are not from the same clonal group, the probability of cells <italic>c</italic> and <italic>c</italic>′ from the same cells given data (i.e., denominator) has smaller value. Thus, <inline-formula id="IEq13"><alternatives><tex-math id="M29">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
